                  p.event-date February 26, 7:30 pm - Crawford Family Forum
                  p 
                    strong: em Punk in Africa 
                    | documents the untold story of the multi-racial punk movement triggered by the political and social upheavals in South Africa, Mozambique, and Zimbabwe during Apartheid. This subculture represented a radical political impulse and its legacy continues today as an emerging generation of bands use their music to confront contemporary political challenges and uncertain identity issues.
                  p KPCC hosts <strong>Grand Performances</strong>, a presentation of the L.A debut of this film, followed by a discussion of how race factored into how the music was created and how it was received. A panel of musicians, including <strong>Ivan Kady</strong> (rhythm guitar, National Wake) invite you to share in the conversation. <strong>Steve Hochman</strong> (KPCC contributor, Los Angeles Times regular) moderates.
                  ul
                    li 
                      | 7:00pm: Doors Open
                    li 
                      | 7:30pm: Program Begins
                  p Admission is FREE, but RSVPs are required. To RSVP, visit <a href="http://scpr.org/forum">scpr.org/forum</a>.
                  p.caption <em>Punk in Africa</em> was directed by Keith Jones and Deon Maas and runs 82 minutes.
